{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/sciatica-lumbar-radiculopathy/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"61580b78-914f-553d-929e-e7509b48b968","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 8e3438b9-e4f2-4955-bf8d-2e8d2ffa6cf5 --><h1>Sciatica (lumbar radiculopathy): Summary</h1><!-- end field 8e3438b9-e4f2-4955-bf8d-2e8d2ffa6cf5 -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 6e6c0d5e-2ca6-41e0-ba96-8b2f8baed0cf --><!-- begin field 82364c39-5dca-440e-bece-89d1451763bc --><ul><li>Sciatica is the term for symptoms of pain, tingling, and numbness which arise from nerve root compression or irritation in the lumbosacral spine.</li><li>Symptoms of sciatica typically extend to below the knee — from the buttocks, across the back of the thigh, to the outer calf, and often to the foot and toes.</li><li>Nerve root compression may be caused by:<ul><li>A herniated intervertebral disc — in about 90% of cases.</li><li>Spondylolisthesis.</li><li>Spinal stenosis.</li></ul></li><li>Risk factors which may increase the risk of developing sciatica include:<ul><li>Strenuous physical activity, for example, heavy lifting or jogging.</li><li>Whole body vibration, for example, driving.</li></ul></li><li>Complications of sciatica include:<ul><li>Permanent nerve damage.</li><li>Psychosocial problems.</li><li>Loss of employment.</li></ul></li><li>The prognosis is worse for women and people who have greater functional impairment or pain.</li><li>Management of sciatica involves:<ul><li>Checking for red flag symptoms and signs which may indicate a serious underlying cause such as cauda equina syndrome, spinal fracture, cancer, or infection. If present, admission or urgent referral should be arranged depending on clinical judgement.</li><li>Assessing the person's risk of back pain disability using a risk stratification tool.</li><li>Providing adequate analgesia for people with low back pain.</li><li>Providing information about its expected time course, self-help measures, advice about staying active, resuming normal activities, and returning to work as soon as possible.</li><li>Offering people at higher risk of back pain disability referral for group exercise, and/or cognitive behavioural therapy, and/or physiotherapy.</li></ul></li><li>Referral: <ul><li>Admit or refer urgently to a neurosurgeon or orthopaedic surgeon if there is progressive, persistent, or severe neurological deficit, depending on clinical judgment. </li><li>If symptoms are not improving or are worsening, refer for group exercise, with or without cognitive behavioural therapy, and/or physiotherapy, and/or consider referral to specialist sciatica or low back pain services for consideration of an epidural corticosteroid/local anaesthetic injection.</li><li>Assessment for radio frequency denervation, or spinal decompression may also be indicated for some people with sciatica when non-surgical treatment has not improved pain or function.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 82364c39-5dca-440e-bece-89d1451763bc --><!-- end item 6e6c0d5e-2ca6-41e0-ba96-8b2f8baed0cf -->","topic":{"id":"ad9c3284-4348-51f2-bbdc-8dd5e93fe217","topicId":"1d568c4f-007a-4c46-a757-366c49d1468c","topicName":"Sciatica (lumbar radiculopathy)","slug":"sciatica-lumbar-radiculopathy","aliases":["Radiculopathy (lumbar) - sciatica"," Lumbar radiculopathy - sciatica"],"chapters":[{"id":"61580b78-914f-553d-929e-e7509b48b968","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"03bfe5a6-4c9c-5d2b-be5c-806c18081f98","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","subChapters":[]},{"id":"2d07cbef-097c-52e8-aca3-605dda07ba5c","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","subChapters":[{"id":"99267823-da67-5e95-a5e6-61d268a8dbee","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"3a12122a-5c0b-50d0-b642-4fd721314790","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},